        <div class="rlo-content-memo"> Gamma (&#947;) rays are energy from the nucleus</div>
        
        Gamma (&#947;) rays are a form of ionizing electromagnetic radiation, 
        and are uncharged (unlike &#945; and &#946; radiation). A gamma photon 
        is a packet of electromagnetic energy emitted from a nucleus in an excited state. &#947; ray 
        photons from <strong>nuclear decay</strong> have energies in the range 
        ~100keV â€¦10MeV.
        
        Often following the decay of a parent nuclide (by &#945;, &#946; or electron capture), 
        a daughter nuclide is left in an excited state 
